description.text:
Our pool pump has a timer but in order for it to work and come on every day it needs to be plugged in. My wife and I got tired of having to unplug it everytime it rained and sometimes we couldn't get to it and then it would trip the circuit. So I made this to shield it from the elements while it was plugged in. We havent had a problem since.
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rQb_la7oalA&feature=player_detailpage

• Print both top and bottom parts off.
  • Use some spare 3mm filament to hinge
  • Silicone to the side of the house around the outlet

title: Replicator Fan Deck - Easy Fan Replacement

description.text: Replacing the fans on a Replicator can be a real pain. I've published a simple replacement for the OEM spacers, which I've heard had been spawned by something evil:(http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:29030) This is the next step. A part of something I'm working on and will make pulling the extruders apart for maintenance a joy... Well, I might be exaggerating a bit :-/

This makes a "deck" on which your fans sit. All the spacers are mounted exactly where they should be, so all you have to do is:
  • Set the heat sinks
  • Set the fan deck
  • Set the fans
  • Bolt it all together.
    • I tell ya, being lazy has its benefits. btw, I dislike rafts and supports, so you won't need them.

This piece clamps onto the two parallel threaded rods between the Z motors on a prusa or mendel reprap 3d printer. Pass the filament through the hole on the top and into the extruder.
Can be used with dual extruders as well, only need to enlarge the top hole a bit if you're using 3mm filament. The elliptical bell-like structure allows for free movement of the extruder along the X-axis without stressing the filament too much.

title: BeagleDrone Quad Copter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: Work in progress

Working on a remix that will use a BeagleBone Black board. I will update more as I go along. I'm still trying to work out the software to get stable flight, but the new body and arm design is much stronger and more rigid. If you wish to fly this quad with a more off the shelf flight controller, there are many options to choose from. All you have to design is the bolt-on board mount for the board you choose. If you do make one please post your make! Its nice to know that your hard work is appreciated :-) Videos:
https://youtu.be/r2XgoH-J0qQ
https://youtu.be/0JYt6nY9qHk Feel free to ask questions or leave comments. Thanks to Hovership for inspiring this project!

Future Goals
  • Camera for FPV flying
  • Switch to the much smaller Intel Edison board

Update 7:
Completely new body and arm design allows passing the wires through the same socket so there are no ugly wires hanging out. Body is aerodynamic and adds cooling ports for optimal air flow. If you wish to use other flight controller boards you can redesign your own board mount to sit on top of the battery cage.

Update 6:
IT FLIES!
https://youtu.be/pXgDGT49fZc

Update 5:
  • New pentagon shaped motor arms for strength and an internal wire guide
  • Lid to with some breakaway support material (shouldn't need support generation from slicing tool)
  • Improved battery door is still a work in progress
  • updated the BBB mount to fit the MPU9250 sensor board

Update 4:
  • Added prop gaurds to the motor arms and put a slit in the side of the motor arm for easy swapping of arms

Update 3
  • Updated the body shape and added holes for the motor wires.
  • Put a wire channel under the motor arm and extended the arm
  • Added a WireGaurd to hold the ESC's and wires into the chassis
Update 2: Updated the body for some weight saving, Added a battery door and have mounts for raspberry pi and Beaglebone (black rev c is what I'm using)

Update 1: I have just completed a re-design of the bottom half of the body. After printing it out it looks promising. A couple tweaks are needed to get some parts to fit and possibly a little add some cut outs to drop the weight a little.

Parts List:
  • M3 screws in various lengths ~ 6mm - 14 mm
  • M3 standard nuts ~ 10 pcs
  • GY-521 board from ebay (accellerometer + Gyro - MPU 6050 chip)
    OR
  • GY- 9250 board (accel, gyro, and Mag MPU-9250 chip)
  • BeagleBone Black Rev C
  • UWN200 Wireless adapter
  • 4 x Turnigy Multistar 15A V2 ESCs
  • 4 x Cobra 2204/32 motors (1960Kv)
  • 2 x Gemfan 6x3 blades
  • 2 x Gemfan 6x3 counter rotating blades
  • Zippy Compact 2200mAh 25c 3 cell battery
  • Battery monitor with LEDs and Alarms

title: Compact Spool Holder and Guide for MakerFarm Prusa i3

description.text:
I needed a way to mount filament spools to the back of my MakerFarm Prusa i3. Lots of designs of thingiverse are either cumbersome, really flimsy or take up too much room.  
My design is compact, efficient and does not extend the space taken by the printer. You can easily fit 2 spools on a 8 inch i3. This setup would be perfect for a dual extruder mod.

Printing Print the both parts at at least 80%, its not worth the hassle of the thing breaking and dropping a heavy spool onto your print bed Filament Guides You will need some strong all purpose adhesive to attach the guides behind the screen. The guide should be attached centrally, Dont position the guide too close to the spool, doing so will cause it to be pulling filament laterally from the spool you want to be pulling the filament close to the direction it would natural unroll in. If you are going for a dual spool setup place them 10cms apart and feed the filament from the left into the right guide so that they would be crossing over. Spool mounts The spool mounts hook over the top plate and should be placed in the far right or left corners. Its not necessary to glue the spool holders but i recommend it just incase the machine is accidentally knocked. The mount is designed to be a tight fit, you may need to remove the top plate to fit the mount on. Additionally you may need to cut a piece out of the triangular support frames if your spools are particularly wide and you don't want to cause additional wear on the extruder. (See the attached pictures)

comments.text: You don't need to do it atleast %80. I did %15 and I'm using PLA. It is quite strong.
